3 WHEREAS, enactment of the District of Columbia Home Rule Act by Congress on December 24, 1973,
4 and ratification of the Charter Referendum by a majority of the voters of the District of Columbia on May 7,
5 1974, reorganized the District of Columbia by granting limited powers of local self-government to an elected 13-
6 member Council of the District of Columbia and an elected Mayor of the District of Columbia to "relieve
7 Congress of the burden of legislating upon essentially local District matters". However, Congress granted no
8 local control over the judiciary and reserved "the right, at any time, to exercise its constitutional authority as
9 legislature for the District, by enacting legislation for the District on any subject, whether within or without the
10 scope of legislative power granted to the Council â€¦ including legislation to amend or repeal any law in force in
11 the District"; and
12 WHEREAS, historically, Congress and the President of the United States have interfered with the
13 District of Columbia's local self-government and Home Rule by enacting resolutions disapproving, amending,
14 and repealing actions of the Council of the District of Columbia and the Mayor of the District of Columbia --
15 including cases concerning the location of chanceries on December 20, 1979, sexual assault reform on October
16 1, 1981, schedule of heights on March 12, 1991, and a revised criminal code on March 20, 2023 -- and by
17 imposing budget riders that control and limit the use of locally raised tax revenue, including cases concerning
18 reproductive health services, cannabis use, and statehood advocacy; and
19 WHEREAS, on multiple occasions, a majority of the voters of the District of Columbia have approved
20 initiatives and referendums expressing a desire for statehood, most recently on November 8, 2016, through
21 which 85.69% of voters:
22 (1) agreed that the District should be admitted to the Union as the State of New Columbia;
23 (2) approved the Constitution of the State of New Columbia;
24 (3) approved the proposed boundaries between the State of New Columbia and the federal
25 enclave; and
26 (4) agreed that the State of New Columbia shall guarantee an elected representative form of
27 government; and
28 WHEREAS, other state and territorial legislatures in the United States have introduced, debated, and
